status_message_cleaned: All aboard! The cultural heart of Glacier National Park, Rogers Pass NHS Mount Revelstoke and Glacier national parks, offers a unique history of the Canadian Pacific Railway Company, and is a beautiful spot to elore for those who ️ to ski. But wait… Make sure not to forget your Winter Permit! ? Glacier National Park is home to the world’s largest mobile avalanche control program! Together with the Canadian Armed Forces, Parks Canada conducts avalanche control with artillery to ensure safety of transportation throughout the park, resulting in daily openings and closures. In order to ski in this area, visitors must take part in the Winter Permit System. Learn more about how you can get your permit here: To celebrate , we're featuring ALL of our + places across our social media accounts. Stay tuned!

status_message_cleaned: Winter is the perfect time to view wildlife in Riding Mountain National Park! From the majestic moose to the shy lynx, it’s one of the premier wildlife viewing destinations in Manitoba. Remember: never feed wildlife and always keep a safe distance. status_message_cleaned: During the First World War, Winnipeg native Christopher O’Kelly (1895-1922) enlisted with the th Battalion (Winnipeg Rifles) and later transferred to the nd Infantry Battalion. In October , O’Kelly led his troops in capturing enemy positions and guns near Passchendaele, Belgium, and resisting fierce counterattacks for which he was bestowed the Victoria Cross. O’Kelly returned home to a hero’s welcome in . Only a few years later, while on a prospecting trip, he was lost on a lake in northern Ontario during a storm. Canada Remembers

status_message_cleaned: Happy Halloween! Did you know it’s also the last day of Bat Week?? As part of a landscape restoration project at Georgian Bay Islands National Park, staff needed to find out if bats were taking up residence in an old maintenance shed. The park’s Resource Conservation team used an ultrasonic acoustic detector and found Little Brown Bats sleeping in the building. They were able to determine exactly when the bats moved out in the fall, so while the bats were away for winter vacation down south, staff installed 'bat boxes' all around the area so they had nice new homes to move into when they returned in the spring.

status_message_cleaned: Did you know the Massasauga Rattlesnake is one of Canada's most unusual snakes and one of the most threatened! This solitary, passive and timid rattlesnake relies on camouflage to avoid detection, shaking its tail in warning when it feels threatened. Preferring flight to confrontation, it rarely strikes, doesn't pursue people and doesn't always inject venom when it bites.

status_message_cleaned: Fire crews continue to do everything possible to slow the progress of the wildfire and protect critical infrastructure, park resources, and the community of Waterton. Kenow Fire Information Update – Unified Command: September , ; :15 FIRE MOVEMENT AND BEHAVIOUR • Fire is now firmly established in the Cameron Valley along the Akamina Parkway. • There is also fire in the Tamarack Basin which is eected to grow and move into the Blakiston Valley and towards the Red Rock Parkway. • We continue to monitor the fire progress. • Structural protection units will be activated if necessary. • Extensive infrastructure and facility protection is installed within the townsite including high volume pump and sprinkler systems around the perimeter of town. • Highways and are now closed at the boundaries of Waterton Lakes National Park. • We are eecting similar weather and intense fire behaviour tomorrow. SMOKE • Intense fire behaviour is generating significant smoke. Wind direction and temperature inversions may result in low-lying smoke in areas north of Waterton, especially at night. • Exercise caution while driving in the area, especially at night. Check AB for driving conditions. Speed limits or closures may be put in place. • Wildfire smoke affects people differently. People with pre-existing health conditions or sensitivities to air pollution are at risk of worsened symptoms from smoke eure. For smoke and air quality alerts visit: WHAT’S OPEN AND CLOSED… • Waterton Lakes National Park is Closed: • Calgary Forest Protection Area south of Highway is Closed: To subscribe or unsubscribe to these updates contact the Fire Information Officer assistant at elisabeth.caron.gc.ca or -247-0075. For media inquiries contact the Fire Information Officer at john.stoesser.gc.ca or -859-5127. For general inquiries, call our Information Line at -859-5109 or kenowfire.waterton.gc.ca

status_message_cleaned: Kenow Fire - Waterton Lakes National Park: September , ; :15hr Parks Canada and RCMP have safely evacuated all residents and non-essential personnel from the park. The Waterton townsite is secured. Admittance at the gate is limited to essential personnel. Intense fire behavior and low visibility caused a risk to safety. To ensure safety, Parks Canada evacuated Waterton. We understand this is a stressful situation and thank everyone for their cooperation, making this a safe and efficient evacuation process. The fire did not cross Sage Pass or South Kootenay Pass into the park and helicopters were able to bucket water later in the afternoon. Fire crews enhanced Waterton’s infrastructure and facility protection. Yesterday afternoon we successfully burned out approximately hectares of vegetation near South Kootenay Pass, removing this fuel in anticipation of increasing wind and fire behaviour today. status_message_cleaned: Happy International Day of Rock! 🤘 If you're not a musician, rock out by visiting one of our beautiful Rocky Mountain Parks. Did you know the Canadian Mountain Parks are a designated UNESCO World Heritage site? Some of the best-known mountain scenery on Earth is concentrated in a set of seven parks in the Canadian Rocky Mountains, including four national parks. The Burgess Shale, in Yoho, contains one of the world’s most significant finds of marine fossils. Photo taken in Yoho National Park. Destination British Columbia

status_message_cleaned: Today is National Blueberry Day! Did you know that berries are an important high quality food source for bears? By mid-July to early August, the fruits of berry producing shrubs begin to mature. On the drier east slopes of the Rocky Mountains, buffaloberry is most common, and on the moister west slopes of the Rockies blueberry and huckleberry shrubs grow. status_message_cleaned: Roughly kilometres southeast of Montréal, Fort Chambly National Historic Site rises proudly at the foot of the Richelieu River rapids. Built in to defend the colony, this stone fortification was preceded by three wooden forts. The fort has preserved the main elements of its original architecture so that you truly feel like you’re walking in the steps of a French infantryman from the th century. status_message_cleaned: During the mid-16th century, large numbers of right and bowhead whales drew whalers from the Basque region of Spain and France to the Strait of Belle Isle, where they established a major whaling port at Red Bay. For some years, Basque whalers made the dangerous, month-long journey across the Atlantic to hunt whales and produce the oil that lit the lamps of Europe. See original Basque artifacts, remains, and restored chalupa at Red Bay National Historic Site in Newfoundland. To celebrate , we're featuring ALL of our + places across our social media accounts. Did you know also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

status_message_cleaned: On this day in four Caterpillar tractors began dragging the ,300-ton S.S. Klondike II from the Whitehorse shipyards to her current location next to the river at the far end of town. Over eight tons of Palmolive Princess Snow Flake soap lubricated the steel cradle and wooden skids on which she moved. It took weeks to complete the move! Now restored to her original appearance, the S.S. Klondike was designated a National Historic Site in . To celebrate , we're featuring ALL of our + places across our social media accounts. Did you know also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

The landscape and wildlife of the ,890 sq km national park is seen by those privileged few willing to travel kilometres north of the Arctic Circle. The landscape features rolling hills, three major rivers, steep canyons, waterfalls, rare Bluenose west caribou and the continent’s fiercest predators. status_message_cleaned: This V-E Day, we’re remembering the who served in Canada’s Merchant Navy and aided Allied victory in the Second World War. From December until the end of the war in , Canadian shipyards on both coasts, and along the St. Lawrence River, undertook a massive emergency shipbuilding campaign to deliver hundreds of desperately-needed vessels to support the Allied war effort. Naval ships like destroyer HMCS Haida National Historic Site escorted merchant convoys to protect against submarine and air attacks.

status_message_cleaned: The Fenian Brotherhood was formed in the United States in . They sought independence for Ireland from Britain and the establishment of an Irish Republic. The American Fenians planned a series of raids to seize the transportation network of Canada, in order to force the British to exchange Ireland’s freedom for possession of Canada. They planned and partly executed raids in Ontario, Quebec, Manitoba and the Maritimes in , and . This extremely rare example of a Fenian jacket was taken from a Fenian prisoner in Quebec in May of . Discover more artefacts under our care by following on .

status_message_cleaned: The beluga whale, nicknamed the “sea canary” because of its diverse and frequent vocalisations, is a fascinating species which lives in a complex social structure. With its white skin, prominent forehead and lack of dorsal fin, it is easily recognizable among marine mammals. The St. Lawrence beluga is a year-round resident of the St. Lawrence River and depends on the Saguenay-St. Lawrence Marine Park to feed and rear its young. We are working with the Department of Fisheries and Oceans and others to encourage the recovery of this endangered species by enhancing protection of its critical habitat. Awareness campaigns, patrolling and new regulations have reduced the threats on belugas caused by boat traffic. Follow our tips on how to interact with in our parks: 9

status_message_cleaned: Ancient Murrelets (or Night Birds in the Haida language) – are a handsome black and white seabird of the North Pacific: the "penguin" of Canada. Ancient Murrelet colonies in Gwaii Haanas are threatened by invasive rats that arrived with the first sailing ships. These birds are a barometer of the health, both of the marine ecosystems and the remote islands on which they breed. With the Haida Nation and several Canadian and international partners, we have successfully restored breeding habitat for the Ancient Murrelet on three islands. status_message_cleaned: The Northern Leopard Frog has a very distinctive call that sounds like a door creaking open, followed by a little chuckle sound. Once the most wide-spread frog in North America, it started to mysteriously disappear from much of southwestern Canada, including Waterton Lakes National Park in Alberta, in the late s. We are taking northern leopard frog egg masses from Grasslands National Park, where the frog populations are healthy, and bringing them back to Waterton Lakes. Our scientists are also working alongside the Calgary Zoological Society to take the search for the missing frogs to the genetic level using an innovative environmental DNA (eDNA) monitoring technique. Follow our tips on how to interact with in our parks: 9

status_message_cleaned: Located on a peninsula jutting out into Lake Erie, Point Pelee is not only the southernmost national park in Canada, it’s the very southern tip of the country itself. Point Pelee is also home to a whopping species at risk – more than any other national park in the country. This includes the monarch butterfly, a species threaten by extreme weather and habitat loss. Point Pelee is working to restore the savannah areas that provide vital habitat for the monarch.

status_message_cleaned: All her life, Katharine McLennan nurtured a deep passion and commitment towards the history and preservation of the Fortress of Louisbourg in Cape Breton, where she was from. For years, she did extensive research to help tell the story of Louisbourg, and, after World War I, she was at the forefront of a civil group aiming to preserve the Fortress of Louisbourg site. Their work led to the opening of the Louisbourg Museum in and the partial reconstruction of the Fortress in the s. Katharine was named "Honorary Curator" of the museum and served in this capacity for over twenty years.

status_message_cleaned: It’s National Frozen Food Day! Did you know flash-freezing technology was inspired by Inuit ice-fishing practices in Canada? Rock caches are a traditional means of storing food in the North. Natural gaps in between rocks channel air flow, acting like a coolant, to keep food fresh or frozen. Tuktut Nogait National Park is home to an area called “Many Caches,” where you can find, you guessed it, many, many caches! Who knew areas like this are to thank for your modern-day frozen dinners!

status_message_cleaned: Hey ! Join us at Rouge National Urban Park for Canada June -25 from noon until noon and help us count and celebrate the amazing diversity of life found across Canada! A BioBlitz is an event that focuses on finding and identifying as many species as possible in a specific area over a short period of time. At a BioBlitz, scientists, families, students, teachers, and other community members work together to get an overall count of the plants, animals, fungi, and other organisms that live in a place. Registration for scientists and skilled naturalists is now open! For folks of all ages wanting to learn more identification and field work skills, registration for Guided Bioblitz sessions opens March . To register as a scientist visit . The Rouge is hosting one of Bioblitz events happening across the country as part of Canada celebrations. Visit to find a Bioblitz near you! A special thanks to our event partners - Royal Ontario Museum, Canadian Wildlife Federation, The Toronto Zoo, BIObus_Canada, and Toronto and Region Conservation (TRCA).

status_message_cleaned: Happy World Wildlife Day! : To protect whales, such as the St. Lawrence beluga and the blue whale, our staff has been studying... their food! Why? To identify feeding grounds. The findings were then used to inform the shipping industry, who agreed to reduce the speed of vessels in the main feeding grounds in order to reduce the risk of collisions with whales. This is a great example of how Parks Canada is leading by using science to support wildlife protection. To learn more about this initiative and other Parks Canada species at risk success stories, visit our website: .
